üá≠üáπ–ì–∞–∏—Ç–∏ left without senators amidst the worst crisis in history
  
The departure of the last 10 senators in Haiti marked the end of a democratically elected government in a country plagued by gang violence, a humanitarian crisis and a cholera outbreak. This was reported by The Washington Post.  
  
The last elected senators in Haiti's government ended their term of office. This has left the poorest state in the Western Hemisphere without a president and without a parliament.  
  
Haiti's government as it stands is led by Prime Minister Ariel Henri, who still has not set an election date. Opponents accuse Henri of dictatorial ambitions and possible involvement in the assassination of former president Jovenel Moise in 2021.  
  
"We have taken a huge step backward. Democracy is an empty word in Haiti today," said Dunois Eric Cantave, who is a member of the Montagne Accord, a powerful opposition group made up of civil society groups and political figures.
